# Tier 3 (TF-fused depth conversion) baseline
# Date: 2026-04-23  |  Commit: fb92135  |  Hardware: AMD Ryzen 9 7950X
# Command: cargo bench --bench bench_t3_tf_fused
#
# Throughput at 4096px:
#
#   sRGB U8 → Linear F32   24.26 GiB/s   fast (LUT-based, SIMD-dispatched)
#   HLG U16 → Linear F32    6.16 GiB/s   scalar
#   Linear F32 → sRGB U8    4.56 GiB/s   **5× slower than reverse**
#   Linear F32 → HLG U16    4.44 GiB/s   scalar
#   PQ U16 → Linear F32     2.68 GiB/s   scalar
#   Linear F32 → PQ U16     1.39 GiB/s   worst — scalar PQ OETF
#
# Findings:
#
# 1. sRGB U8 → Linear F32 is the most common conversion in SDR pipelines
#    (every resize that cares about linear light). Already ~25 GiB/s — good.
#
# 2. **sRGB asymmetry**: Linear F32 → sRGB U8 is 5× slower than the reverse.
#    The forward direction uses a 256-entry LUT indexed by u8. The reverse
#    has to evaluate a rational polynomial + divide per lane. Divide is ~15-20
#    cycles on x86 and is the likely bottleneck. Worth checking whether
#    linear-srgb has a faster OETF variant (possibly a larger LUT approach).
#
# 3. PQ and HLG kernels are scalar — confirms the linear-srgb#10 upstream
#    dispatch gap also affects these fused kernels (not just Tier 4 TF-only).
#    Worst: Linear F32 → PQ U16 at 1.39 GiB/s (17× slower than sRGB forward).
#
# Action items:
#   - Investigate sRGB OETF asymmetry (linear-srgb local to us or upstream).
#   - Benefit of linear-srgb#10 extends here: PQ/HLG fused kernels would also
#     pick up the dispatched rites if #10 lands in a way that covers u16 paths.
